In LaTeX, you can automatically generate a table of contents using the `\tableofcontents` command in the preamble or at the desired location in your document. Here's an example of how to set up a LaTeX document with an automatically generated table of contents:

```latex
\documentclass{article}

% Define the document title and author
\title{My LaTeX Document}
\author{Your Name}
\date{\today}

% Use the hyperref package to enable table of contents links
\usepackage{hyperref}

% Create the headings and their corresponding labels
\section{Introduction}
\label{sec:intro}

\section{Background}
\label{sec:background}

\section{Methods}
\label{sec:methods}

\section{Results}
\label{sec:results}

\section{Discussion}
\label{sec:discussion}

\section{Conclusion}
\label{sec:conclusion}

% Generate the table of contents in the preamble
\tableofcontents

% The document content
\maketitle

\section{Introduction}
\label{sec:intro}
This is the introduction section.

\section{Background}
\label{sec:background}
This is the background section.

% Include a figure with a label for the table of figures
\begin{figure}[h]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.5\textwidth]{example-image-a}
\caption{Example figure}
\label{fig:example}
\end{figure}

\section{Methods}
\label{sec:methods}
This is the methods section.

\section{Results}
\label{sec:results}
This is the results section.

\subsection{Subsection}
\label{subsec:subsection}
This is a subsection.

\section{Discussion}
\label{sec:discussion}
This is the discussion section.

\section{Conclusion}
\label{sec:conclusion}
This is the conclusion section.

% Create a list of figures and a list of tables using the hyperref package
\clearpage
\printindex
\printbibliography

\end{document}
```

In the example above, we define the document title, author, and date, and use the `hyperref` package to enable table of contents links. We create the headings and their corresponding labels, and then generate the table of contents using the `\tableofcontents` command in the preamble. The table of contents will be automatically updated as you add, remove, or modify sections in your LaTeX document.

