In Java, the `==` operator is used to compare the reference of two objects, not their values. When comparing strings with `==`, you are actually checking if both variables hold the same reference to a string object in the memory.

On the other hand, `.equals()` is the method you should use to compare the values of two strings in Java. When you call `.equals()` on a string object, it compares the character sequences of the two strings lexicographically (character by character).

The situation where you encountered the bug was likely caused by using two different string objects with the same content. Although the strings seemed identical to you, they might have been created at different points in the program or through different methods. When you used `.equals()` instead, it compared the values of the strings, and since the contents were the same, it produced the expected result.

As a general rule, `==` should be used when comparing references to the same object, while `.equals()` should be used when comparing the values of objects, including strings. This is particularly important when it comes to strings in Java, since strings are immutable and are often created at different points in the program.

For example, consider the following code snippet:

```java
String str1 = new String("Hello");
String str2 = new String("Hello");

if (str1 == str2) { // This expression is false
    // The code here will not be executed
}

if (str1.equals(str2)) { // The code here will be executed
    // The code here will be executed when str1 and str2 have the same content
}
```

In the above example, even though the contents of the two strings are the same, they are not the same object in memory. Using the `.equals()` method allows you to compare their values, regardless of whether they are different objects or not.

To solve the problem without using loops or recursion, we can use the bitwise operators in Java. The binary representation of a number n can be expressed as a power of three if and only if the binary representation of n can be written as a continuous string of 1's, followed by a power of two. For example, the binary representation of 27 (which is a power of three) is 111011, which can be written as 1 (a power of one) followed by 111011, which is a power of two.

Here's how you can implement this solution in Java:

```java
public boolean isPowerOfThree(int n) {
    if (n <= 0) return false;
    int intPowerOfThree = 1;
    int logBaseTwo = 0;

    // Calculate the log base 2 of n
    while ((n & 1) == 0) {
        n >>= 1;
        logBaseTwo++;
    }

    // Check if the remaining bits form a power of three
    intPowerOfThree = 1;
    for (int i = 1; i <= logBaseTwo; i++) {
        intPowerOfThree *= 3;
        if (n != intPowerOfThree) return false;
        n %= intPowerOfThree;
    }

    // If we reach this point, then n is a power of three
    return true;
}
```

This solution first checks if the input number is negative or zero, and returns false if it is. Then it calculates the log base 2 of n by shifting the bits one by one until the least significant bit is set. The number of shifts is the log base 2 of n. Finally, it checks whether the remaining bits can be expressed as a power of three by calculating the powers of three and comparing them with the remaining bits, until the remaining bits are zero. If this check passes, then the input number is a power of three.

